[2] Cholera - Myanmar (Rangoon)
Date: Thu 24 Mar 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Democratic Voice of Burma [edited]
<http://english.dvb.no/news.php?id=4322>

People did die in cholera outbreak in Rangoon, said local residents
-----------------------------------------------
Although health authorities recently insisted that no one had died from the
cholera outbreaks in Thinganggyun, North Okkalappa and Hlaing Thaya
Townships in Rangoon, local residents told the Democratic Voice of Burma
(DBV) that at least 2 women had died from the epidemic.
The 2 victims are said to be workers from Hlaing Thaya Township, Industrial
Zone-3, Shwekyaryan, and Yes Clothing Factories, and both of them were
originally from the rural areas.
"There are 152 sufferers of cholera in Hlaing Thaya at the moment. 130
people are being treated in Hlaing Thaya Hospital. 22 people are in Insein
Hospital," said an unnamed local resident who visited the hospitals recently.
The local authorities are telling people not to eat snacks and salads sold
by roadside hawkers, but, to no avail, as they are living a hand to mouth
existence, and they have to keep on selling banned food. At the same time,
people mainly blame the unclean communal water supply for the outbreaks.
The outbreaks in Thainganggyun and Hlaing Thaya are in a critical state,
and the officials from the Health Ministry should handle the cases with
care, commented the resident.
At the same time, there have been reports of deaths in North Okkalapa due
to the cholera outbreak, but a doctor denied them.
"Not really. There must be only one or 2. Those who are not good from the
beginning died, of course. If it is cholera, we do not keep them here. If
it is cholera, we send them to Waybargi," she told DVB.
